{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_cicerone_ver01/data/sn83016244/00271761302/1937121101/0557.xml":{"full_text":"Associated Press Day Wire\nService.\nFor Devoted to the\nBest Interests of Key West\nVOLUME LVIU. No. 294.\nAuto Smash On Duval\nSt In Early Morning\nThree Occupants Of One\nCar Slightly Injured;!\nOther Auto Was Struck\nWhile Parked\nEdison Knowles, familiarly;\nknown as Red, decided lo fake a\nride early this morning, selecting\na car which is the property of a\nMr. Kenney.\" Knowles took as\nhis companions R. Melrose and\nWm. Bell, members of the ship's\ncompany from the Steamship\nSummerleaf which is undergoing\nrepairs at the Porter Dock Cos.\nThe ride was not of long dura\ntion, in fact it was very brief, as\nwhen the riders reached a point\njust north of Eaton street ,on Du\nval street, the car made ungentle\ncontact with the rear end of the\nImperial, owned by Dr. Julio De\nPoo. and the result was a com\nplete wreck of both the cars.\nKnowles said he was driving\nalong at a moderate rate of speed,\nabout 20 miles per hour, and\nwhen turning out, or trying to\nturn out, to miss the car which\nwas parked in front of Dr. De\nPoo\u2019s residence, the wheels of the\ndriven car were found to be lock\ned, and it was impossible to turn\nout to avoid the accident.\nThe speed of the travelling car\nwas 20 miles, said the driver, but\nfhffe results imttmtrd' a greater\nspeed, it was said by experienced\nmen, as the larger car, the Im\nperial, was driven up on the side\nwalk, and the front end smashed\ninto a pole and was wrecked. The\nsmaller car crashed into the rear\nof the larger, and resulted, na\nturally, in the demolition of the\nrear of the larger car and com\nplete wreck of the striking auto\nIn fact the only puzzling part\nof the results is why nobody was\nseriously injured. Knowles re\nceived* several minor injuries.\nBell complained of strained\nmuscles and tendons in the left\nleg, and Melrose had a slight cut\non the forehead, presumably from\nilying glass.\nThe steering wheel of the\nsmaller car was smashed into\nsmall pieces, and was tom com\npletely from the post, glasses\nbroken in both cars and oCher\ninjuries, indicate a terrific iai\npact, and it was said\ninconceivable Hbvp' ft car\u2019.wayd\nling at but JpeT aour,\ncould \u2018tybti 1 tfyipv\nage. and none\u2018 of the ridor? be\nseriously Injured*\nWhen the arraigned\nfor hearing thlfhio'fnihg. Knowles\nwas fined SIOO or 60 days, having\nbeen found guilty of driving an\nautomobile while under the influ\nence of liquor, and causing injury\nto another car. His companions\nwere fined $25 each, but this fine\nwas later reduced to sls each.\nThe charge against them was\ndrunk and disorderly.\nIn connection with the forego\ning case W. D. Hainning was ar\nraigned for carrying intoxicants\ninto the city jail for prisoners. He\nwas sent to the jail by the ship\u2019s\ncaptain to ascertain the condition\nof the men. and decided to do the\nGood Samaritain. He took two\nbottles of \u201csuds\u201d, one for each of\nhis shipmates, and his \u201cgood\ndeed\u201d for the day cost him S3O.\nSTEAMER OZARK\nCOMES TO PORT\nSteamship Ozark, of the Clyde-\nMallory Lines, arrived in port 2:30\no\u2019clock this morning with heavy\nshipments of lumber for local\ndealers and a number of creosoted\npoles for naval station activities.\nThe vessel came from Jackson\nville and Miami, ami after dis\ncharging cargo sailed 11 o'clock\nfor New Orleans.\nIMPROVE THE LOOKS OF YOUR HOME WITH A GREEN LAWN. OUR LINE OF LAWN MOWERS AND GARDEN IMPLEMENTS IS COMPLETE. SOUTH FLA,\n\u00aeljr Strtj West Citizen\nCandidate For Congress\nVisiting Key West\ny,v j\nHENRY H. FILER\nANTON FISCHER\nRETURNS HERE\nWIDELY-KNOWN ARTIST TO\nREMAIN DURING WIN\nTER SEASON\nAnton Otto Fischer, widely\nknown artist, and who is deeply\ninterested in Key West, as evi\nt dence by his return for another\nstay for the season, is back for\nthe winter, accompanied by Mrs.\nFischer, and daughter. They have\nleased, through the firm of John\nson and Johnson, the Carey resi\ndence, 1401 United street.\nOne of Mr. Fischer\u2019s most at\ntractive pictures, at least to Key\nWesters, is that story of this sec\ntion of the waters of the Atlantic\nwhich appeared several months\nago in a widely-read weekly\nmagazine, and which was illus\ntrated by a painting by Mr. Fisch\ner, which depicted a sea-scene\nshowing a wrecked schooner fly\ning the British flag, in distress\nposition, and another sailing ves\nsel, close hauled, on the stem of\nwhich was shown, \u201cFlying Fish, j\nI Key West.\u201d 1\nCUBA ARRIVES\ni FROM HAVANA\nfl U\nVESSEL LEFT LATE IN AFT\nNOON ENROUTE TO\nTAMPA\n\nSteamship Cuba, of the P. and\nO. S. S. Cos., arrived yesterday aft\nernoon from Havana with two\nfirst and three second cabin pas\nsengers for Kev West; 21 first and j\ntwo second cabin passengers for\nTampa. a j\nArrivals for Key West: Amelia\nCanal, Judith OTarrill. Julio\nBenavides, Maria Berrera de Rod\nriguez, Gregorio Gonzalez.\nAmong the items listed on the\nship\u2019s manifest were three sacks\nof mail for Key West; five tons\nof freight and 96 sacks of mail for\nTampa.\nCuba sailed at 5 o'clock with\nbookings from Key West as fol\nlows: H. Mandell, Mrs. J. R. Hor\nlett, W. R. Bcdinger, and several\nj second cabins.\n\nTRADE UP; VALUE DOWN\nGeneva. Switzerland. While\nthe volume of world trade was al\nmost back to its 1929 level in June\nof this year, the gold value of this\ntrade remained only 47 percent,\nof the 1929 value, according to\nfgiures published by the League\nof Nations monthly statistical\nbulletin. In other words, despite\nall trade barriers, the world is\nexchanging about as much goods\nas at the height of prosperity, but\nis getting only half as much gold\ntherefor. j\nHENRY FILER\nIN RACE FOR\nCONGRESSMAN\nFORMER KEY WESTER VISIT\nING HERE MEETING OLD\nFRIENDS AND ACQUAINT\nANCES r\nArriving in Key West last night\nfrom Miami, was Henry H. Filer,;\nformer Key Wester, who is mak\ning the race for Congressman\n.from the Fourth Congressional\nDistrict.\nMr. Filer, who was born in Key\nWest, and who is also a nephew of\nAllan B. Cleare, Sr., paid a call at\niThe Citizen office today in com\npany with Mr. Cleare.\nj Mr. Filer, while here, is inci\ndentally meeting many old friends\nand forming new acquaintances,\n>in connection with his activities\n;in the interest of his candidacy.\n:He stated that he was more than\ndelighted to be back in the Island\nCity again. He proposes to return\nto Miami on Monday.\nMr. Filer, former chairman of\nthe Dade County School Board\nand past President of the Florida\ni Education Association, will seek\nI the post now held by Congress\njman Mark Wilcox, who will con\njtest the seat of United States Sen\nator Claude Pepper in the forth\ncoming national elections. The\nFiler announcement was made\nI shortly after news of Congress\nman Wilcox\u2019s plans were made\npublic.\n\u201cI am entering the race fully\nconscious of the tremendous re\nsponsibilities of the office,\u201d Mr.\nFiler said in disclosing his candi\ndacy. \u201cI am now at work sum\nmarizing my platform, which I\nshall release later. Meanwhile, I\nfeel that the public of South Flor\nida should receive assurances that\nI will put forth the same unselfish\nwork in Washington that I have\n.endeavored to perform locally. It\nshall be my purpose, if elected, to\naewe all the puu*pk, xA 4Bfc district\nfaithfully and fairly, showing par\ntiality to no single group, clique\nor faction.\u201d\nMr. Filer was bom in this city,\nbut has lived in Dade County\nsince boyhood. His grandfather\nrepresented the county in the\nstate legislature at the time that\nDade embraced nearly the entire\n1 southeast section of Florida. The\nolder Filer payed a prominent part;\n!in the passage of legislation which i\nj enabled Henry M. Flagler to ex- j\n'tend his railroad system south\nward from St. Augustine into Mi\n;ami, and thence by the overseas\nroute to Key West.\nTwice president of the Florida\nj Education Association, Mr. Filer is\nknown throughout the state as the\nchampion of the state\u2019s school ap\npropriation bill, which finances\nthe state's educational system on\na basis of SBOO for each teacher\nunit. He commaded the educa\ntion essociation during the trying\ndays of the 1935 session of tfye\nstate legislature, and succeeded in\nproviding the schools with their\nfirst adequate financial setup. Be\ncause of his services to the schools,\nhe was made a life mftiinber of the\nFlorida Education Association. i\nHe frst entered politics in 1912\nwhen he was elected treasurer of\nDade county. He was re-elected\nand held the post until its aboli\ntion by the state legislature. He\nwas a member of the first city\ncouncil of Miami Beach and later\nwas elected to the county school\nboard. He was a member of the\nboard for 16 years, 12 of them as\nchairman.\nHe is married and has two\ndaughters, both graduates of the\nFlorida State College for Women\nat Tallahassee, Florida. He is a\nMason, an Elk. and a member of\nGrace Methodist church, where he\nwas chairman of the board of\nstewards for twenty years.\nBUSTER CEREZO\nGIVEN HEARING\nBuster Ccrezo, charged with at\ntempt to commit an assault, was\narraigned this morning in the\ncourt of Peace Justice Enrique\nEsquinaldo for preliminary hear- j\ning. and entered a plea of not\nguilty.\nAfter hearing the evidence in\nthe case, the magistrate decided\nthere was not sufficient grounds\nfor holding the accused, and dis\ni missed the case. i\nKEY WEST, FLORIDA, SATURDAY, DECEMBER 11, 1937.\nLeonard White Injured\nIn Fall From Bridge\nLeonard White, son of Mr. and\nMrs. J. O. White, of Caroline\nstreet, fell from Pigeon Key\nBridge yesterday afternoon and\nsuffered a compound fracture of\nthe left leg near the ankle.\nResponding to a call from No\nName Key, Benjamin Sawyer,\nmanager of the Lopez Funeral\nHome, left in the ambulance for\nNo Name, accompanied by Depu\n'REAL INCOME\u2019 OF CONSUMER\nRISES DESPITE TRADE SLUMP\nNEW SPECIMENS AT\nTROPICAL AQUARIUM\nDay by day new specimens\nare being added lo the col\nlection at the Key West\nTropical Aquarium, and Joe\nRomero, who is in charge of\nthe exhibits, said yesterday\nthat by the time the season\nstarts he expects to have a\nmuch more varied display\nthan that of last year.\nWithin the past few days\nthere has been placed in the\ntanks several new species, in\ncluding a red drumiish. a\nlarge stingray and a small\noctopus. The stingray is\nabout as large as any which\nhave been in the tanks for\nsome time, exclusive of\ncourse, of the school of\nleopard rays which were in\none of the oval tanks last\nseason.\nMr. Romero said that he\nhad made the necessary ar\nrangements with a number\nthe strange fish caught, and\nis also being successful in\ngetting a number of interest\ning fish and invartabrates in.\nhis traps.\nTEMPERATURES\ni\u2014\nLowest Highest\nlast night last 24 hrs.\nAbilene 28 36\nApalachicola 3O 48\nAtlanta t 18 34\nBoston 18 34\nBrownsville 40 44\nBuffalo 16 20\nCharleston 30 52\nChicago 10 16\nCorpus Christi 42 44\nDenver 24 50\nDetroit 14 20\nDodge City 16 24\nDuluth \u20142 10\nEastport 24 34\nEl Paso _ 48 66\nGalveston 42 44\nHatteras 38 46\nHavana _\nHelena 32 40\nHuron 2 14\nJacksonville 30 52\nKansas City 6 24\nKEY WEST 58 69\nLittle Rock 22 32\nLos Angeles 60 62\nLouisville 14 26\nMiami 52 70\nMpls.-St. P. 0 14\nNashville 14 30\nNew Orleans 32 4a\nNew York 24 26\nOklahoma City 24 26\nJtaatacola 26 40\nPhoenix 48 72\nPittsburgh 10 22\n\u2022St Louis 14 26\n)Salt Lake City _ 48 54\nSan Francisco _ 60 68\nSit. Ste. Marie 2 24\nSeattle 50 56\nTampa 34 56\nWashington 20 36\nWilliston 6 14\nWytheville 10 24\nREPOSTS \"BITTER COLD\"\nMrs. Braxton B. Warren, who\nwas visiting with her son-in-law\nand daughter, Mr. and Mrs. Clem\nent Hudson in Miami, returned\nThursday and reported \u201cbitter\nicoid weather\nty Sheriff Ray Elwood, placed\n1 young White in the ambulance,\n'and he was brought to the city\n|and placed in a hospital.\nThe Citizen was informed today\nthat the fall from the bridge to\ni the water was about 30 feet.\nYoung White fell on a launch and\nthen into the water. It is believ\ned that the injury to the leg was\n.caused by striking the anchor on\nthe deck of the launch.\n(Special to The Cittern)\nMINNEAPOLIS, Dec. 11.\u2014A\ngain of six cents on the dollar\nover a year ago in \u201creal income\u201d\nof the average citizen explains\nwhy the business recession has\nnot cut seriously into some trades,\naccording to a study made public\nhere today by Investors Syndi\ncate.\n\u201cWhen Mr. and Mrs. Average\nHouseholder have $1.13 for every\n$1 they had a year ago,\u201d explain\ned the consumer\u2019s study, \u201cand\nwhen they have to spend only\n$1.06 for every $1 they spent a\nyear ago, they will continue to\nbuy briskly, provided, of course,\nthey see prospects of their income\ncontinuing.\u201d\nNational consumption capacity\nactually is at the best levels since\nthe depression, because the pres\nent business recession has not yet\ncut seriously into the \u201creal in\ncome\u201d of American consumers. If\nthis consumption capacity is\nmaintained and exercised:, the\nquestion of top-heavy inventories,\nn&r worrying the ecotipmists,\nshould not long prove trouble\nsome.\nPublic buying power has been\naccelerated by the increased cash\nincome being placed in the hands\nof the farm population. Urban\ncash income when contrasted with\nNovember 1, 1036, is not particu\nlarly impressive because it was at\nthis season last year that the wave\nof wage increases began to swell\nsubstantially.\nWages show the largest gain in\ncash incomes, being up 14 cents\non the dollar as contrasted with\nNovember i, 1936. Investment in\ncome, despite the recent collapse\nof security prices, ranks second in\npoint of gain, dividend and inter\nest payments combined averaging\neleven cents on the dollar more\nthan at the start of November a\nyear ago. Other income, which is\ncomposed largely of payments to\nfarmers and individual business\nowners, stands at $1.09 in relation\nto last year\u2019s dollar. Salaries,\nhowever, are up only six cents on\nthe dollar, contrasted with the\nsame month in 1936.\nLiving costs, by their advance\nof six cents on the dollar over a\nyear ago, have somewhat offset\nthe gain in cash incomes.\nFood, the biggest single item on\nthe budget of the average house\nholder, shows the smallest gain in\ndaily expenses when compared\nwith a year ago, because only\n$1.02 today is required to buy the\nsame amount o' nourishment that\ncould be had for SI.OO on Novem\nber 1, 1936.\nRents\u2014a particularly signific\nant figure to those wondering\nabout resumption of building ac\ntivity\u2014have gone up so much that\nit requires sl.lO to rent an apart\nment, flat, cottage or house for\nevery $1 asked at the start of No\nvember, 1936.\nClothing, another important\nitem in living expenditures, is up\nsix cents on the dollar over a year\nago, being the last of the major,\nitems to stage an advance. Mis\ncellaneous expenses, such as\namusements, automobiles, mani\ncures, shaves and so on, are live\ncents on the dollar higher than\nthey were at the beginning of No\nvember. 1936. i\nThe difference between the\ncash income of the average citi\nzen and his cash outgo is his real\nincome. This \u201creal income** of\n$1.06 is not a mere subtraction of\ncash income from cash outgo\u2014\nwhich would be an index of sav\nings rather than real income\u2014but\nan average of relative figures of\nincome and outgo designed to\nshow how the cost of living af\ni fects the adjusted income dollar.\nAdditional Funds Obtained\nFor Improvements At Fort\nJefferson National Monument\nKey West Youth Commits\nAnother Act Of Thievery\nRobert Izquierdo, not quite 11\nyears old, is presenting a problem\nto officials of both county and\ncity by continually getting into\ntrouble through acts of petty\nthievery, and his pernicious ac\ntivity was again brought to the at\ntention of the sheriffs department\nThursday night when a report\nwas received that he was suspect\ned of the theft of a pocketbook\ncontaining $11.95.\nThe complaint of the loss was\nlodged by members of the family\nof Hilary Whalton, who reside on\nDuval street, near Olivia. They\nwent to see Peace Justice Enrique\nEsquinaldo and after hearing the\ndetails, he decided to turn the in\nformation over to Chief Deputy\nSheriff Bernard Waite.\nMr. Waite learned that Izquier\ndo had been seen in the vicinity\nof the Whalton home, decided he\nwas a suspect, having, in fact,\nconfessed on previous occasions to\nthefts at the homes of Wm. W. De\nmeritt, Ernest Hemingway, and\nother homes and residences.\nCalling at his home, Mr. Waite\nfound him absent and dwellers in\nthe home said they did not know\nwhen he would return. \u201cMight be\nabsent all night,\u201d as he sometimes\nleft in the evening and did not\nreturn until the following day.\nThe search was continued and\nafter making several calls and\nasking some questions, it was\nlearned that he was in one of the\ntheaters and seated on the fourth\nrow. A visit was paid to the the\nater and Izquieido was seen try\ning, ineffectually, to hide from the\neyes of the deputy.\nHe was taken from the show\nand to the office of Justice Es\nquinaldo where he was put\nthrough a gruelling questioning\nthat would have broken down the\ndefensive denials of hardened\ncriminals. He won the hearts of\nthose who were listening and they\ndecided that he was being impos\ned upon, and was decidedly not\nguilty.\nMr. Waite thought differently,\nand took him to the county jail\nfor questioning. He still stoutly\n\u2018SCOOTER\u2019TOURIST IN KEY\nWEST HAS COME 12,500 MILES\nArriving in Key West this\nmorning was a gentlemen\nfrom Missouri by the name\nof Tom Herridge. Like ell\ngentlemen from Missouri Mr.\nHerridge states that he re\nquires absolute proof of\neverything tolA him. So\nwhen he first heard of a num\nber of tourists using the new\nmotor scooters to tour the\ncountry. Mr. Herridge de\ncided to find out the truth\nof the statement for himself.\nPromptly he purchased a\nscooter and in July started\noff.\nSince that time he has\nTENDER IVY Will\nSTART HOMEWARD\ni Lighthouse Tender Ivy is today\nmaking preparations for starting\nthe homeward trip and will prob\nably be in port by Christmas, said\nSuperintendent Wra W Demerits\nof the Seventh District, this morn\ning.\nThe tender, said Mr. Demerit!,\nhas completed the buoy work in\nTampa Bay. This morning die\nwas at Tampa where die will re\nfuel and take on provisions. This\nafternoon the vessel will be at St\nPetersburg.\nLeaving there the vessel will at\nonce resume the activities, which\nat this time consists, mostly, of\nrelieving buoys, and will start\nthis work at Sarasota.\nasserted his innocence, and swore\nby everything sacred that he had\nnothing to do with any theft, and\nso pitiful were his pleas of inno\ncence that he won the sympathy\nof prison inmates, who were\nshocked at the persistence of Mr.\nWaite.\nHowever, the chief deputy has\nhad much experience with this\ntype of youthful transgressors,\nand especially boys of Robert\u2019s\ntype, several of which are roam\ning around this city, and he per\nsisted, and at last told the boy\nthat he was going to put him in\none of the cells. He did so, slam\nmed and locked the door, turned\noff the light and took his depar\nture.\nHe had gone but a few steps\nwhen an inmate of the jail called\nto him. Returning he was advis\ned that the boy wanted to tell him\nsomething, and this something\nwas a confession of the theft.\nMr. Waite said that when he\nfirst caught the boy he just casual\nly .went through hia pockets, and\nwas amazed when the boy un\nbuckled his Knickerbocker and\nfrom around his leg at the knee,\nunwrapped a handkerchief, in one\ncorner of which was tied practic\nally the entire amount he had tak\nen from the pocketbook.\nFollowing this he was taken\nback to the vicinity of the Whal\nton homd where he showed where\nhe had tossed the pocketbook aft\ner removing the contents. From\nthere he was led to the Whalton\nhome and while the family were\nseated at the dining table he went\nin and placed the pocketbook and\nmoney on the table. Imagine the\nconsternation when the family\nlearned that the boy who had won\ntheir sympathy, was really the\ntheief.\nThe boy was afterward turned\nover to his mother for the usual\nthrashing he receives after one of\nhis escapades, as he cannot be\nheld a prisoner, and cannot be\nsent to the reform school, as he\nis not quite 11 years old, and the\nyouth limit is 12 years at the\nstate institution.\ntravelled 12.500 miles, going\nthrough 18 states in this coun\ntry and two provinces of\nCanada. The scooter will be\ntaken over water soon or the\nfirst time when Herridge\ntakes it to Cube in the next\nlew days end later to the\nBahamas.\nIn the spring, he will leave\nagain, for northern fields and\nplans to visit Nova Scotia.\nThe scooter, which differs\nfrom the ordinary type in\nthat it carries a trailer, is e\nsmall machine with 12 inch\nwheels. It has held up re\nmarkably in its long run.\nSEA SCOUTS UNIT\nHOLQ MEETING\nSea Scouts held an Interesting\nmeeting Thursday night at the\nOdd Fellows* building when new\nmembers were admitted to the or\nganization.\nA basketball team was formed,\nwith plans made for putting on\ngames. The rmtter of purchasing\nuniforms will be taken up again\nwhen the head of the organization\nreturns to die city at which time\nhe will be contacted in reference\nto the subject.\nMany other activities were car\nried on during the course of the\ni meeting.\nKey West, Florida, has the\nmost equable climate ia the\ncountry; with an average\nrange of only 14* Fahrenheit\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nOne Of Activities Wilt- Be\nReplanting Parade\nGround In Center 01\nImmense Structure\nAnother allotment of funds has\nbeen allocated for use at Fort\nJefferson Marians 1 Monument.\nAdvices to this effect wore re\nceived at the office of. project\nsupervisor BwCtMoraM, of the\nWPA. The total sum allotted fee\nthe work is ,SII,OOO.\nAmong the work items which\nare to be done at the fort is sal\nvaging material, and replanting\nthe parade ground. Other work\nin connection with theee projects\nhave been outlined.\nActivities will start about De\ncember 17, it was said, and It\nmen and a supervisor will be as\nsigned to the work. Arrange\nment* for transportation of the\nworkers are now boing made,\nand it is anticipated that all will\nbe in readiness to leave and got\nreedy for the work by the date\nof start of operations.\nJUDGE GOMEZTO\nLEAVE ON SUNDAY\nRETURNING TO kIAMXTO Mi-\nSUMS COURT SESSKOft\nt nf**tnr; vj\nJudge Arthur Gomez, of ths\nEleventh Judicial Circuit, who ar\nrived this week to attend fun\neral services for his mother, Mrs.\nIda E. Gomez, will return to Mi\nami tomorrow to resume the court\nsession which was interrupted by\nhis necessary departure.\nSeen in his chambers this mam\nin g, Judge Gomes said that there\nare seven murder cases remaining\ndPKi docket, of the nine which\nwere scheduled for hearing One\ncase which was disposed of pri\nor to his return this week result\ned in conviction by a Jury, and\nthe other defendant entered a plea\nof guilty to a charge of man\nslaughter.\nMRS. MARY COHEN\nDIES HERE TODAY\nBODY BEING PREPARED POM\nSHIPMENT TO HOME\nIN NEW YORK\nMrs. Mary Cohen, 68, native at\nRichmond Hill. New York, died\nthis morning 525 o\u2019clock Ua the\nhome of Rabbi Joseph Male, ear\nner of Simon ton and Southard\nstreets.\nThe body has been placed with\nthe Lopez Funeral Home to be\nprepared for shipment and will be\nsent out via Overseas Transpor\ntation company this evening to\nMiami where it will be met by\nHarry Mandeibaum, son-in-law at\nthe deceased, who will accompany\nit home.\nMrs. Cohen visited in Key West\nlast year and returned for anoth\ner visit, when she was \u25a0\u2666rich\u2014\nand failed to recover.\nSurvivors are: Son-in-law and\ndaughter, Mr. and Mrs. Harry\nMandeibaum. and one son, Mor\nton Cohen, of Hvimvfd ty*^","height":"25209","width":"19545"}}
